&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type:square;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in Present Continuous Tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The structure of the Present Indefinite Tense is -&amp;nbsp;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Subject (Singular)&amp;nbsp;+ Verb ( s/es form ) + Object&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Subject (Plural) + Verb (1st form) + Object&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Eg. He cuts his nail.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Singular subject - (Any name, he, she, it)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plural subject - They, these, those etc&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;list-style-type:square;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;simple present tense&lt;/strong&gt; is used to talk about something that happens always &lt;strong&gt;regularly, often, sometimes or never.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 4.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;blowing his own trumpet&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means to praise oneself, often excessively. (अपनी ही प्रशंसा करना)

	&lt;ul&gt;
