	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Sentence (2) explains the historical context of the name Lakshadweep.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; 1, 4, 3, 2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: 2, 1, 3, :&lt;/strong&gt; Starting with historical context (2) before introducing the main topic (1), diminishes the coherence and logical flow of the paragraph.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: 1, 3, 4, 2:&lt;/strong&gt; Provides a mix of introduction and details but places the historical context (2) at the end, which disconnects from the preceding information.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: 2, 3, 4, 1:&lt;/strong&gt; Starting with historical context (2) misses the opportunity to properly introduce the geographical topic (1) before providing specific details (4), and ends with a broader introduction (1) which disrupts the flow.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;masterminded; ruthless&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;mastermind&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means to plan a difficult activity in detail and ensure it happens successfully. (योजना बनाना और सफलतापूर्वक क्रियान्वित करना)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;ruthless&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means not thinking or worrying about any pain caused to others; merciless. (निष्ठुर या निर्दयी)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The other options do not fit the context of planning a detailed activity and the merciless suppression of opposition.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complete Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;He &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;masterminded&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; a &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;ruthless&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; suppression of all opposition.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Crafted&lt;/strong&gt;: means skillfully created or planned but does not imply planning a complex activity and ensuring its success alone.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Drafted&lt;/strong&gt;: means preparing a preliminary version of a document; does not fit the context of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Watertight&lt;/strong&gt;: means tightly sealed or perfect in design; does not imply merciless actions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Systematic&lt;/strong&gt;: means done according to a plan or system; does not imply merciless actions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;B&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Segment A, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Aniket lives&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; is grammatically correct. It has a proper subject-verb agreement.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Segment B, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;in the small apartment&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; contains a minor article usage error. The correct usage should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;in a small apartment&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; since a specific apartment is not being referred to previously within a given context. We generally use &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; when we are referring to specific things or instances that both the speaker and listener are aware of.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Segment C, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;in the suburbs&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; is grammatically correct as the usage of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;in&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is appropriate for indicating location.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the segment containing the error is &lt;strong&gt;B&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt; should be: &lt;em&gt;&amp;#39;Aniket lives &lt;strong&gt;in a small apartment&lt;/strong&gt; in the suburbs&amp;#39;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;instinctive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;instinctive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means relating to or prompted by instinct; done without conscious thought.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;adaptive&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means having the ability to change or be changed to fit altered circumstances.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;behaviours&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; refers to the way in which one acts or conducts oneself, especially toward others.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The context of the sentence is about natural responses and actions, making option 1 the most appropriate.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complete Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;The &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;instinctive&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;, natural way to express anger is to respond aggressively. Anger is a natural, &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;adaptive&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; response to threats; it inspires powerful, often aggressive feelings and &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;behaviours&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;, which allow us to fight and to defend ourselves when we are attacked.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Extraordinary (असाधारण)&lt;/strong&gt;: means very unusual or remarkable.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Seductive (लुभावनी)&lt;/strong&gt;: means tempting and attractive; enticing.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Unreasonable (अतार्किक)&lt;/strong&gt;: means not guided by or based on good sense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Phenomenal (अद्भुत)&lt;/strong&gt;: means very remarkable; extraordinary.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Atypical (असामान्य)&lt;/strong&gt;: means not representative of a type, group, or class.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Booming (तेजी से बढ़ना)&lt;/strong&gt;: means having a period of great prosperity or rapid economic growth.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; Option 1)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, the word&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;seek&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the most appropriate choice&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It means to attempt to find or obtain something.&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It&amp;#39;s his job to seek out new customers&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct sentence is &amp;quot;The toddler decided to make a mess because he wanted to seek the attention of its parents.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The other options do not fit the context of the sentence:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Elicit:&lt;/strong&gt; This means to draw out a response, answer, or fact from someone, which does not fit the context.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Please:&lt;/strong&gt; This means to make someone happy or satisfied, which is not the toddler&amp;#39;s intention in the context given.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Extract:&lt;/strong&gt; This means to remove or take out something, which is not relevant to the context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Sombre.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;lively&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means full of life and energy; active and outgoing. (जीवंत)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The lively atmosphere at the carnival made everyone feel happy and excited.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Sombre&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to something that is dark, dull, or serious; not cheerful or lively. (उदास)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The mood at the funeral was sombre, with everyone reflecting on the loss.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, we can infer that the opposite of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;lively&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;sombre&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Durable&lt;/strong&gt; (टिकाऊ): Able to withstand wear, pressure, or damage; hard-wearing.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The durable fabric of the sofa ensured it lasted for years.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cheerful&lt;/strong&gt; (प्रसन्न): Noticeably happy and optimistic.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Her cheerful demeanor brightened up the entire room.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speedy&lt;/strong&gt; (तेज़): Moving or capable of moving at high speed.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The speedy delivery service ensured the package arrived the next day.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt; Millennium.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Millennium&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means a period of one thousand years, especially when calculated from the traditional date of the birth of Christ. (सहस्राब्दी)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The year 2000 was celebrated as the beginning of a new millennium.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Millennium&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English, the correct preposition to use with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;abide&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;in this context is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by.&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;So the correct sentence would be: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;He does not abide by the rule.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;abide&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;essentially means to accept or act in accordance with a rule, decision, or recommendation. And when used in this sense, it typically is accompanied by the preposition &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 4&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Here&amp;#39;s why the other options are incorrect:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;at:&lt;/strong&gt; The preposition &amp;quot;at&amp;quot; is not grammatically correct in this context. Although &amp;quot;at&amp;quot; can indicate a location or a point in time, it isn&amp;#39;t used with &amp;quot;abide&amp;quot; to indicate following a rule.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;of: &lt;/strong&gt;The preposition &amp;quot;of&amp;quot; can denote a relationship between a part and a whole, an origin, or a cause, among other things. However, it is not used with &amp;quot;abide&amp;quot; in the sense of adhering to a rule.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;for: &lt;/strong&gt;Although &amp;quot;for&amp;quot; is used to indicate the purpose of an action, it is not used with the verb &amp;quot;abide&amp;quot; to convey the meaning of obeying or following a rule.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;The project had been completed by them before the deadline.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;Past Perfect&lt;/strong&gt; Tense and in Active Voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a Past Perfect Tense from Active voice to Passive voice: Interchange the object and the subject with each other - object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + had + V3 + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + had been + V3 + by Subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;They had completed the project before the deadline. (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The project had been completed by them before the deadline. (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;They&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the project&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Apply the rule changes - &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;had completed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;had been completed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; The project had been completed by them before the deadline.

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;The cake will be baked by Sarah.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;Future Simple&lt;/strong&gt; Tense and in Active Voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a Future Simple Tense from Active voice to Passive voice: Interchange the object and the subject with each other - object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + will + V1 + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + will be + V3 + by Subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Sarah will bake the cake. (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The cake will be baked by Sarah. (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Sarah&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the cake&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Apply the rule changes - &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;will bake&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;will be baked&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; option 3.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence: &lt;/strong&gt;The cake will be baked by Sarah.

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;They said they would arrive late.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;When changing from direct to indirect speech, we typically shift from future tense to conditional tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;So, &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;will&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; changes to &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;would&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The first person plural &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;we&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; changes to the third person plural &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;they&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; referring to the same group of people.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The order of words &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;They said&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; remains the same in indirect speech.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option a.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;This change from &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;will&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; to &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;would&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is part of the general shifting of tenses when we turn direct speech into indirect speech.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;The bridge will have been completed by the engineers by next summer.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The original sentence is in the&lt;strong&gt; active voice, &lt;/strong&gt;where the subject performs the action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The structure is:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;subject + future perfect verb (will have completed) + object.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In a&lt;strong&gt; passive voice &lt;/strong&gt;sentence, this structure changes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The object moves to the beginning of the sentence, becoming the new subject, and the verb changes to match.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The general structure is:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;object + auxiliary verb to be (in the correct tense) + past participle of the verb + (by + subject).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;The bridge&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is now the focus of the sentence&lt;strong&gt;, &amp;quot;will have been completed&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is the &lt;strong&gt;future perfect passive&lt;/strong&gt; form of the original verb phrase, correctly projecting the completion of the action in the future, and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by the engineers&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; retains the original actor of the action.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;Option 3&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Important information has been provided by Jessica.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;Present Perfect&lt;/strong&gt; Tense and in &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;Voice.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a Present Perfect Tense from Active voice to Passive voice: Interchange the object and the subject with each other - object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + has/have + V3 + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + has/have + been + V3 + by + Subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Jessica has provided important information. (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Important information has been provided by Jessica. (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the given sentence is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Jessica&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the given sentence is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;important information&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Apply the rule changes - &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;has provided&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;has been provided&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence: &lt;/strong&gt;Important information has been provided by Jessica.

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;The project will have been completed by them before the deadline.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in &lt;strong&gt;Future Perfect&lt;/strong&gt; Tense and in &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;Voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a Future Perfect Tense from Active voice to Passive voice: Interchange the object and the subject with each other - object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + will have + V3 + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + will have been + V3 + by + Subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;They will have completed the project before the deadline. (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The project will have been completed by them before the deadline. (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;They.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the project.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Apply the rule changes - &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;will have completed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;will have been completed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; The project will have been completed by them before the deadline.

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;The house is being painted by them.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;Present Continuous&lt;/strong&gt; Tense in &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;Voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a Present Continuous Tense from Active voice to Passive voice: Interchange the object and the subject with each other - object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + is/are + V1+ing + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + is/are + being + V3 + by Subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;They are painting the house. (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The house is being painted by them. (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the given sentence is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;They&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the house&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Apply the rule changes - &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;are painting&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;is being painted&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; option 3.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence: &lt;/strong&gt;The house is being painted by them.

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;The house is cleaned by them every week.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;Present Simple Tense&lt;/strong&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;Voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a &lt;strong&gt;Present Simple Tense&lt;/strong&gt; from &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;voice to &lt;strong&gt;Passive &lt;/strong&gt;voice: Interchange the object and the subject with each other - object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + V1+s/es + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + is/are + V3 + by Subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;They clean the house every week. (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The house is cleaned by them every week. (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;They&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the given sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the house&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Apply the rule changes - &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;clean&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;is cleaned&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; The house is cleaned by them every week.&lt;/p&gt;
Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Option 1.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt; &amp;lsquo;Cookies are being baked by Sarah&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;Present Continuous&lt;/strong&gt; Tense in &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;Voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a &lt;strong&gt;Present Continuous&lt;/strong&gt; Tense from &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;voice to &lt;strong&gt;Passive &lt;/strong&gt;voice, we interchange the subject and the object - the object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive one.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + is/am/are + verb+ ing + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + is/am/are + being + past participle + by subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;In the given sentence:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Sarah&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;cookies&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Applying the rule changes, &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;is baking&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;are being baked&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence: &lt;/strong&gt;Cookies are being baked by Sarah.&lt;/p&gt;
Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2.&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;The cat was chased by the dog.&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;past simple&lt;/strong&gt; tense in &lt;strong&gt;Active &lt;/strong&gt;Voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;To change a past simple tense from Active voice to Passive voice, the object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive sentence and the subject becomes the &amp;#39;agent&amp;#39; or doer of the action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Subject + past simple form of the verb + object (Active Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Object + was/were + past participle + by subject (Passive Voice)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;In the given sentence:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The subject of the sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;The dog&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The object of the sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the cat&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Applying the rule changes, &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;chased&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; will be changed into &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;was chased&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence: &lt;/strong&gt;The cat was chased by the dog.&lt;/p&gt;
Therefore, the correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Option 4&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;A hue and cry is being raised and the furniture is being broken by the people.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in the active voice, and we have to convert it into a passive voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Before evaluating the options, let&amp;#39;s understand the structure of active and passive voices.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Active voice structure:&lt;/strong&gt; Subject (doer of action) + Verb + Object (receiver of action)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Passive voice structure: &lt;/strong&gt;Object (as subject) + Auxiliary verb (&amp;#39;be&amp;#39; variant as per tense) + Main Verb (past participle) + &amp;quot;by&amp;quot; + Agent ()&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Active voice sentence: &lt;/strong&gt;People are raising a hue and cry and are breaking the furniture.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In this sentence:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subject: &lt;/strong&gt;People &lt;strong&gt;Verb: &lt;/strong&gt;are raising, are breaking &lt;strong&gt;Object: &lt;/strong&gt;a hue and cry, the furniture&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We should preserve the tense (&amp;#39;are raising&amp;#39; i.e., present continuous tense) while converting the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Passive voice form of the above sentence would be:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;A hue and cry is being raised and the furniture is being broken by the people.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Now, let&amp;#39;s assess each option:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;1)&amp;quot;A hue and cry is being raised and the furniture is being broken by the people.&amp;quot; This is the &lt;strong&gt;correct conversion&lt;/strong&gt; into the passive voice. It retains the original meaning and tense.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;2)&amp;quot;A hue and cry is being raised and the furniture are being broken by the people.&amp;quot; This sentence incorrectly uses &amp;#39;are&amp;#39; for &amp;#39;furniture&amp;#39;, it should be &amp;#39;is&amp;#39; because &amp;#39;furniture&amp;#39; is an uncountable noun.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;3)&amp;quot;Hue and cry and the furniture is being broken.&amp;quot; This sentence is incomplete and does not correctly represent the passive form.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;4)&amp;quot;A hue and cry has been raised and the furniture has been broke.&amp;quot; This sentence uses a tense (present perfect) that doesn&amp;#39;t match the original sentence (present continuous), and &amp;#39;broke&amp;#39; is incorrect; it should be &amp;#39;broken&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Based on the analysis, the correct alternative is &lt;strong&gt;option 1) &amp;quot;A hue and cry is being raised and the furniture is being broken by the people.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; which correctly expresses the sentence in the passive voice.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 1&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;This sky-scraper will have to be pulled down as the town planning regulations have not been complied with.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in active voice and we have to convert it into passive voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The rule for forming the passive voice is as follows:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Active: Subject (doer of action) + Auxiliary Verb + Main Verb + Object (receiver of action)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;​Passive:&amp;nbsp;Subject (previously the object or receiver of action) + Auxiliary Verb + Past participle form of main verb + by ...(Agent, i.e., the original subject)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Active Voice Sentence: &lt;strong&gt;You will have to pull down this sky-scraper as you have not complied with the town planning regulations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Let&amp;#39;s break this sentence down:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subject: &lt;/strong&gt;You &lt;strong&gt;Auxiliary Verb: &lt;/strong&gt;will have to &lt;strong&gt;Main Verb: &lt;/strong&gt;pull down / complied &lt;strong&gt;Object: &lt;/strong&gt;this sky-scraper / the town planning regulations&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The passive voice form of the above sentence would be: &lt;strong&gt;Object + auxiliary verb + &amp;quot;be&amp;quot; + past participle of main verb + by + subject&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Now, let&amp;#39;s assess the given options:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 1) &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;This sky-scraper will have to be pulled down&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;by you&lt;/span&gt; as the town planning regulations have not been complied with.&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;This is a&lt;strong&gt; correct passive voice conversion&lt;/strong&gt; of the original sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 2) &amp;quot;This sky-scraper will have to be pulled down by you as the town planning regulations have not been complied by you.&amp;quot; It&amp;#39;s also a correct conversion into passive voice, but it repeats the agent (&amp;quot;you&amp;quot;) twice, which is unnecessary and makes the sentence less fluent.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 3) &amp;quot;This sky-scraper will be pulled down as the town planning regulations have not been complied with.&amp;quot; This omits &amp;quot;have to,&amp;quot; changing the meaning of the sentence slightly - it&amp;#39;s not as strong an assertion as the original.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 4) &amp;quot;This sky-scraper will have to be pulled down as the town planning regulations have not been complied.&amp;quot; This sentence is incorrect as it lacks the preposition &amp;quot;with&amp;quot; after &amp;quot;complied&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, based on our analysis, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;This sky-scraper will have to be pulled down &lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;by you&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;as the town planning regulations have not been complied with.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It preserves the meaning of the original sentence, its tense, and elegantly forms the passive voice without any unnecessary repetition.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 1&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Was it ever made clear how the machine is operated?&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in active voice: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Did any one ever make it clear how one operates the machine?&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In turning it into passive voice, the following transformation rules apply:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Object becomes the subject of the sentence:&lt;/strong&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;Here, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;it&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;made vague in the original sentence, refers to the understanding or clarity of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;how one operates the machine&amp;quot;. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Hence, this vague &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;it&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;becomes the subject in the passive voice, preferred to be represented as &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;was it&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The action verb &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;make&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;in active voice becomes &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;made&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;did&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is replaced with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;was&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;in passive.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;It&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is positioned after &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;was&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;to indicate that we are asking about whether some action was performed on &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;it&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;(&amp;#39;it&amp;#39; being the clarity about machine operation).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Tense is maintained:&amp;nbsp;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;In the active sentence, the verb phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Did...make&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is in the simple past tense, so the passive sentence should also be in the simple past.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;This is done by using &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;was&amp;quot; + past participle (&amp;#39;made&amp;#39;).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The actor of the sentence (anyone or the person who makes it clear) is dropped as it&amp;#39;s not specific and not vital to the sentence meaning in passive form.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The clause &amp;#39;how one operates the machine&amp;#39; is a clause acting as a direct object in active sentence, in the passive it changes to &amp;#39;how the machine is operated&amp;#39;, retaining the information but changing the structure to be more fitting for a passive construction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, option 1: &amp;quot;Was it ever made clear how the machine is operated?&amp;quot; is the correct transformation into passive voice.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It follows all the transformation rules, properly turns the action onto the object, and gives the same meaning as the original active sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The rest of the options do not follow these transformation rules correctly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 1&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;The cyclone did not cause&amp;nbsp; much damage to the life and&amp;nbsp; property in July this year at&amp;nbsp; the Andhra coast.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In order to choose the appropriate active form of the sentence, let&amp;#39;s first understand the difference in the structure between active and passive voice, especially in the context of &lt;strong&gt;simple past tense.&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Active Voice Structure: &lt;/strong&gt;Subject + Past Simple Verb (V2) + Object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;Tom painted the wall.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Passive Voice Structure:&lt;/strong&gt; Object + Was/Were + Past Participle of the Verb + By + Subject.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The wall was painted by Tom.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Now let&amp;#39;s reconsider the original sentence: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Not much damage to the life and property was caused by the cyclone in July this year at the Andhra coast.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The sentence is currently in the passive voice.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The original subject (the cyclone) is found after the verb &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;caused&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;and the preposition &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by&amp;quot;, &lt;/strong&gt;and the objects (life and property) are before the verb.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Applying the active voice structure, we need to rearrange this sentence so that the cyclone (the subject) is performing the action (the verb - cause damage) on the object (life and property).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Out of the options given&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;​The third sentence is correct. &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;The cyclone did not cause much damage to the life and property in July this year at the Andhra coast.&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;maintains the original tense and meaning, and ensures the correct subject is performing the action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the appropriate active form of the given sentence is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;The cyclone did not cause much damage to the life and property in July this year at the Andhra coast.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct sentence is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 3&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;Option 4&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;The students eagerly awaited their results&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence needs to be arranged in a grammatically correct and meaningful way.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English, the subject typically comes first, followed by the verb, and then the object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;eagerly&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is an adverb and should be placed before the verb &amp;quot;awaited&amp;quot; to describe how the action was performed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;their&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a possessive pronoun and should be placed before &amp;quot;results&amp;quot; to show ownership.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 4&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The students eagerly awaited their results&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;The students their eagerly awaited results.&amp;quot; - The placement of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;their&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;eagerly&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is incorrect, disrupting the grammatical structure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;The awaited eagerly results their students.&amp;quot; - This option is completely jumbled and does not form a meaningful sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;Eagerly awaited the students their results.&amp;quot; - The adverb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;eagerly&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is correctly placed, but the structure is incorrect because the subject should come first.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;counsel&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Counsel&amp;quot; refers to lawyers in a case.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a collective noun and may refer to a single lawyer or a team of lawyers representing a party in a legal setting.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, it&amp;#39;s appropriately used in the sentence to mean that the speaker, likely a judge or another authority, has heard from the learned (i.e., highly experienced and expert) lawyers who are representing the parties involved in the case.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For the given sentence &amp;quot;I have heard learned &lt;strong&gt;counsel &lt;/strong&gt;appearing for the parties&amp;quot; correctly denotes that the speaker has heard the arguments or statements made by the lawyers representing different parties in a legal case.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 1&amp;quot;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Option 3&amp;#39; i.e. &amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Is she reciting the poetry?&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The question asks to transform a passive voice sentence into active voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The passive sentence is in present continuous tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The structure for this tense in active voice should be: subject + is/are + verb-ing + object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 3 forms the sentence in active voice correctly.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is-&amp;nbsp; &amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Is she reciting the poetry?&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 1 and 2 don&amp;#39;t maintain the present continuous tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 4 isn&amp;#39;t formed as a question but a statement instead, which changes the original meaning.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Option 1&amp;#39; i.e. &amp;#39;The board members approved the proposal unanimously.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The original sentence is in passive voice and is in Simple Past tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In changing to active voice, the agent &amp;#39;the board members&amp;#39; becomes the subject in active form.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The subject &amp;#39;the proposal&amp;#39; in passive becomes the object in active voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &amp;#39;was unanimously approved&amp;#39; becomes &amp;#39;approved unanimously&amp;#39; to conform to the Simple Past tense in active voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is-&amp;#39;The board members approved the proposal unanimously.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 2: &amp;#39;Was approving&amp;#39; is in past continuous which does not match the tense of the original sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 3: The sentence structure is wrong. The word &amp;#39;unanimously&amp;#39; is misplaced and changes the meaning of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 4: The sentence lacks a consistent structure and the verb &amp;#39;was&amp;#39; shouldn&amp;#39;t be there.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;confidence&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Aplomb&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;means self-confidence or assurance, especially when in a demanding situation. (स्वाभिमान)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;: Ravi handled the tough questions from the panel with &lt;strong&gt;aplomb&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct synonymous word that can replace &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;aplomb&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; in the sentence is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;confidence&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;. (विश्वास or आत्मविश्वास)&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;: She addressed the crowd with great &lt;strong&gt;confidence&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct synonym for &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;aplomb&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;confidence&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is- &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Diffidence&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;: This word means modesty or shyness resulting from a lack of self-confidence. (संकोच)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Apprehension&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;: This refers to anxiety or fear that something bad will happen. (भय or आशंका)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Disquiet&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;: It&amp;nbsp;denotes a feeling of anxiety or worry. (बेचैनी)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&amp;#39; i.e. &amp;#39;Wimbledon&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;Wimbledon&amp;#39; is a district in Southwest London that is most well-known for being the location of the annual Wimbledon Tennis Championships.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;For example: Wimbledon is famed for its annual tennis tournament.&lt;/li&gt;
