&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Even though&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Even though&amp;quot; fits best in this context. It creates the contrast needed in the sentence, suggesting that, despite their lack of time, they completed the project.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Assuming that&amp;quot; is incorrect as it suggests a hypothetical situation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Since&amp;quot; is incorrect as it implies cause and effect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;As soon as&amp;quot; is incorrect because it means &amp;quot;immediately after&amp;quot; and it doesn&amp;#39;t make sense in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;Option 2&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;sees her children&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, the context is the present, the action of waiting is a continuous one and Mrs. Smith will stop waiting once she sees her children.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;lsquo;Doesn&amp;rsquo;t see her children&amp;rsquo; and &amp;lsquo;saw her children&amp;rsquo; don&amp;rsquo;t agree with the concept of waiting &amp;#39;until&amp;#39; something happens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;lsquo;Has seen her children&amp;rsquo; refers that the action is completed, and it does not fit the continuous nature of waiting in this sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, &amp;lsquo;sees her children&amp;rsquo; matches the present tense and also the continuous nature of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;Option 3&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;don&amp;#39;t you?&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence structure you&amp;#39;ve presented indicates a question tagged onto the end of a statement. This is a common form in English known as a &amp;#39;tag question.&amp;#39; The purpose of tag questions is to either confirm the information in the statement or to genuinely ask a question.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the main part of the sentence is positive, the tag at the end is usually negative, and vice versa. In your sentence, &amp;quot;You remember the first place we ate&amp;quot; is a positive statement, so a negative tag (&amp;quot;don&amp;#39;t you?&amp;quot;) is expected to follow.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The choice &amp;quot;don&amp;#39;t you?&amp;quot; fits grammatically because the main verb in the preceding statement is &amp;quot;remember,&amp;quot; which requires the auxiliary verb &amp;quot;do&amp;quot; in simple present tense questions or negations. Since the statement is in affirmatory form, the tag becomes &amp;quot;don&amp;#39;t you?&amp;quot; to make it negative, following the common structure for forming tag questions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;from not staying out too late&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the given sentence is the use of the double negative&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;from not staying,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; which creates a grammatically incorrect construction. The correct form should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;forbade me from staying.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Corrected sentence:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; My parents forbade me &lt;strong&gt;from staying out too late &lt;/strong&gt;during the school week to ensure I prioritized my studies and got enough rest.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When using &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;forbade&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;forbid,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; it is followed by &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;from&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; and then &lt;strong&gt;the gerund form of the verb (the -ing form)&lt;/strong&gt; to indicate the action that is prohibited.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Different example:&lt;/em&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Incorrect: The teacher &lt;strong&gt;forbade the students from not &lt;/strong&gt;bringing any electronic devices to the classroom.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Correct: The teacher &lt;strong&gt;forbade the students from&lt;/strong&gt; bringing any electronic devices to the classroom.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;(d) You will be suspended unless you pay your fees. &amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence needs to express a conditional situation where not doing something (paying fees) leads to suspension.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is typically expressed with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;unless&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;to mean &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;if not.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option (d) &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;You will be suspended unless you pay your fees.&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;correctly uses &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;unless&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;to indicate that suspension can be avoided if the fees are paid.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It correctly communicates the condition to avoid suspension.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option (a) suggests that suspension occurs because fees are paid, which contradicts the logical sequence of such situations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option (b) is incorrect because &amp;quot;unless you don&amp;#39;t&amp;quot; is a double negative that can cause confusion.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The correct phrase is &amp;quot;unless you&amp;quot; followed by the positive form of the verb.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option (c) uses past tense &amp;quot;had paid&amp;quot;, which is inappropriate since the sentence is predicting a future consequence based on a present or future condition (paying fees).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 3&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;otherwise, they face obsolescence.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The correct answer &amp;quot;otherwise, they face obsolescence&amp;quot; clearly conveys a consequence of not innovating amidst rapid technological advancements. It indicates that failure to innovate will likely lead to becoming outdated or obsolete.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;Otherwise&amp;quot; is used to introduce an alternative outcome, essentially warning against the consequences of not adhering to the advice given in the first part of the sentence. It fits perfectly to express the notion that businesses need to avoid the negative outcome (obsolescence) by constantly innovating.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The other options do not convey the sense of urgency and consequence as effectively as &amp;quot;otherwise.&amp;quot; &amp;quot;Unless&amp;quot; suggests a condition, but it doesn&amp;#39;t fit the cause-effect relationship needed here. &amp;quot;While&amp;quot; suggests simultaneity, not consequence, and &amp;quot;if&amp;quot; introduces a condition that doesn&amp;#39;t follow the logical structure of a warning or consequence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Using &amp;quot;otherwise&amp;quot; emphasizes the direct correlation between the need for constant innovation and the risk of becoming obsolete, offering a clear, impactful statement on the importance of adaptation and innovation in the business world.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;Option 1&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;because traffic was heavier than usual&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The use of &amp;quot;despite&amp;quot; at the beginning of the sentence sets up a contrast or an unexpected result. The phrase &amp;quot;he was late for the meeting&amp;quot; is a consequence that needs a reason that contrasts yet explains the initial action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The conjunction &amp;quot;because&amp;quot; is used to introduce a reason or explanation for something that happened. In this sentence, it explains why he was late despite his promise, linking the cause (heavy traffic) with the effect (being late).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The options &amp;ldquo;but he didn&amp;#39;t care much,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;and nobody seemed to notice,&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;so he decided to call ahead,&amp;rdquo; don&amp;rsquo;t serve to explain the causal relationship between his promise to be on time and his eventual tardiness, making them less appropriate completions for the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Option 3 logically fills the gap by providing a specific reason (heavier than usual traffic) for the consequence mentioned earlier (being late), adhering to the cause-and-effect structure implied by the sentence setup.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;Option 3&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is Option (2) &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Rakesh ordered Mahesh to go away&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The reported speech has a sense of order and not question or inquiry.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is so because Rakesh is ordering Mahesh that he should leave.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, asked and inquired cannot be used in the case of ordering.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the case of imperative sentences we use&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;to&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; instead of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;that&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; as a linker.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Say to&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; cannot be used because the reported verb should be in past tense and not in present tense.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct indirect speech of the given sentence is &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Rakesh ordered Mahesh to go away.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;PQRS&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Sentence P introduces what cloud computing offers to businesses following the claim of revolution in S1, providing a logical next step in explaining cloud computing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Sentence Q explains the benefits of the model introduced in P, highlighting scalability and flexibility as key features, making it a natural follow-up to the explanation of the services provided by cloud computing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Sentence R talks about the change in investment strategy for companies, which directly relates to the financial benefits mentioned in Q.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Sentence S elaborates on the outcomes (financial savings and efficiencies) of utilizing cloud computing, following up on the changes mentioned in R before closing with the summarized benefits in S6.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;Option 4&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;so that he can secure a scholarship.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;This sentence suggests a purpose or intention behind excelling in studies. The phrase &amp;quot;so that&amp;quot; introduces the purpose of an action clearly and is the most fitting connector for indicating intent or aim.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;While options 2 and 3 introduce contrast and option 4 introduces a hypothetical situation, none of them directly link to the notion of excelling for a specific beneficial outcome, such as securing a scholarship.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;so that&amp;quot; implies a direct, positive outcome (securing a scholarship) as a result of the action (excelling in studies), adhering to a cause-and-effect structure with a specific goal in mind.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;This completion underscores strategic effort, where excelling in studies is not an end in itself but a means to achieve another significant goal.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;Option 1&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;as long as it is accompanied by substantial investment.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Implementing renewable energy initiatives typically requires significant financial investment for development, infrastructure, and possibly incentivizing adoption, making option 4 the most logical completion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;as long as&amp;quot; introduces a condition that is necessary for the effectiveness of the government&amp;#39;s new policy, emphasizing that without substantial investment, the policy may fail to achieve its goals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Options 1, 2, and 3 do not provide a condition crucial for the effectiveness of the policy in the same manner option 4 does. They suggest possible factors but do not directly address the necessity for financial backing to ensure implementation and success.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Considering the practical aspects of transitioning to or implementing renewable energy policies, significant investment is a realistic and critical requirement, marking option 4 as the most suitable completion.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;lsquo;Option 4&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;Option 3&amp;#39; i.e. &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;beside&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;beside&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is used to indicate that someone or something is next to or at the side of another person or thing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;through&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; suggests movement within or across an area, which is not applicable in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;in&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; generally indicates being inside something, which does not fit with standing near a bridge.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;from&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; typically indicates the point of origin or separation and does not make sense in this context where location or position is implied.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;beside&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Through:&lt;/strong&gt; This preposition suggests movement in one side and out of the other or across something, and is not appropriate for indicating a position near an object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In:&lt;/strong&gt; This preposition is used to express a position within an area or volume, making it unsuited for describing the position next to a bridge.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;From:&lt;/strong&gt; This preposition indicates the point of origin, starting point, or separation, which doesn&amp;#39;t describe a stationary position near an object.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option(1) i.e. &amp;#39;walked; noticed; had stopped; felt; knew&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The actions occur in sequence in the past, which is indicated by the past simple tense (&amp;#39;walked&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;noticed&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;felt&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;knew&amp;#39;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Past perfect tense (&amp;#39;had stopped&amp;#39;) is used for an action that had happened before another action in the past (noticing the silence).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;This sequence of tenses accurately reflects the action sequence and timing as described in the situation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Therefore, the complete sentence is- &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;As I &lt;u&gt;walked&lt;/u&gt; through the park, I &lt;u&gt;noticed&lt;/u&gt; that the birds &lt;u&gt;had stopped&lt;/u&gt; singing and suddenly I &lt;u&gt;felt&lt;/u&gt; a chill. It was as if they &lt;u&gt;knew&lt;/u&gt; something I did not.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option(2) &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;walk; notice; stop; feel; knew&amp;quot; does not correctly sequence the past actions as it mixes the present and past tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option(3) &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;walks; notices; have stopped; feels; knows&amp;quot; incorrectly uses present tense for all actions, which doesn&amp;#39;t match the past events described.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option(4) &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;walking; noticing; stops; feeling; know&amp;quot; presents a continuous or progressive aspect inappropriate for the finished actions indicated.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 2.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Miscellaneous&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means a collection of various items or different kinds; mixed or assorted. (विविध)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The drawer was filled with &lt;strong&gt;miscellaneous&lt;/strong&gt; items like pens, coins, and paper clips.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: Micsllaneous &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;गलत वर्तनी&lt;/span&gt;): This is an incorrect spelling of the word &amp;quot;Miscellaneous&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: Micslleneous &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;गलत वर्तनी&lt;/span&gt;): This is an incorrect spelling of the word &amp;quot;Miscellaneous&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4: Miscellenious &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;गलत वर्तनी&lt;/span&gt;): This is an incorrect spelling of the word &amp;quot;Miscellaneous&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;astonishment&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a synonym of &amp;quot;amazement,&amp;quot; meaning great surprise or wonder. (आश्चर्य)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In the context of the sentence, Leena would be filled with &amp;quot;astonishment&amp;quot; upon seeing the diamond ring as her wedding gift, which fits the scenario of experiencing a strong feeling of surprise.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The other options: &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;haughtiness&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (arrogance), &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;measurement&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (the size, length, or amount of something), and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;happiness&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; (a state of being happy) do not convey the same meaning as &amp;quot;amazement.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complete Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Leena was filled with &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;astonishment&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; when she saw the diamond ring as her wedding gift.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Haughtiness (अहंकार)&lt;/strong&gt;: means arrogance or being disdainfully proud. It does not fit the context of being surprised by a gift.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Measurement (माप)&lt;/strong&gt;: refers to the size, length, or amount of something. It is unrelated to the concept of &amp;quot;amazement.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Happiness (खुशी)&lt;/strong&gt;: means a state of being happy. While it may be a related emotion, it does not specifically convey the sense of being amazed or astonished.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the misuse of the contraction &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;who&amp;#39;s&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; which should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;whose&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Who&amp;#39;s&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a contraction for &amp;quot;who is&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;who has,&amp;quot; whereas &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;whose&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a possessive pronoun.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;whose books&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part B&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;B&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;Mr. Malhotra is a historian &lt;strong&gt;whose books&lt;/strong&gt; have won international acclaim.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A: &amp;quot;Mr. Malhotra is a historian,&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C: &amp;quot;have won international acclaim.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 2&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;appropriate&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means something that is suitable or proper in the circumstances. (उचित)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;It is important to wear appropriate clothing for a job interview.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Appropriate&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;refers to something that is fitting or suitable for a particular purpose or situation. (उचित)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;He made an appropriate comment during the meeting, which was well-received by everyone.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, we can infer that the correctly spelt word is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;appropriate&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Apropriate&lt;/strong&gt; : This is an incorrect spelling and does not have any meaning.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Appropriete&lt;/strong&gt; : This is an incorrect spelling and does not have any meaning.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Approprite&lt;/strong&gt; : This is an incorrect spelling and does not have any meaning.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 3.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;clique&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is a small, exclusive group of people with shared interests or other features in common, who spend time together and do not readily allow others to join them. (गुट)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The high school students formed a clique that was difficult for outsiders to penetrate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt; i.e. clique.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oblique&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;तिरछा&lt;/span&gt;): Neither parallel nor at a right angle to a specified or implied line; slanting.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The artist drew oblique lines to create an abstract pattern.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pique &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;आक्रोश&lt;/span&gt;): A feeling of irritation or resentment resulting from a slight, especially to one&amp;#39;s pride.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;She left the meeting in a fit of pique after her ideas were dismissed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Antique &lt;/strong&gt;(&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;पुराना&lt;/span&gt;): A collectible object such as a piece of furniture or work of art that has a high value because of its considerable age.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;She collects antique jewelry from the Victorian era.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;Option 4&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;immortal&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;never able to die,&amp;quot; which accurately fits the context of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Options like &amp;quot;invincible,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;impervious,&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;invisible&amp;quot; do not relate directly to the idea of not dying, so they are incorrect choices.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Option 4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;: In Indian mythology, most of the Asuras wish to be immortal.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;Invincible&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;unable to be defeated&amp;quot; rather than &amp;quot;unable to die,&amp;quot; which is not correct in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;Impervious&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;not affected by something&amp;quot; and does not fit the context of death or immortality.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;Invisible&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;unable to be seen&amp;quot; and is unrelated to the concept of not dying.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 2&lt;/b&gt; i.e. Quiet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;babble&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means to talk in a confused or excited way. (बड़बड़ाना)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The toddler started to babble as soon as she saw her favorite toy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Quiet&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;refers to making very little or no noise; it is the opposite of talking excessively or noisily. (शांत)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The library is a quiet place where people can read and study without distractions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, we can infer that the opposite of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;babble&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;quiet&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 2 i.e. Quiet&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gossips&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;गपशप&lt;/span&gt;): Talking casually or informally about others, often involving details that are not confirmed as true.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; She loves to gossip about her coworkers during lunch breaks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Talkative&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;बातूनी&lt;/span&gt;): Fond of or given to talking a lot.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;He is a talkative person who enjoys long conversations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rants&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;प्रलाप&lt;/span&gt;): Speaking or shouting at length in an angry, impassioned way.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; He went on a rant about the poor service he received at the restaurant.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct tense is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;have&amp;nbsp;been playing&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;have&amp;nbsp;been playing&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is used in the present&amp;nbsp;perfect continuous tense to indicate that an action was ongoing in the past for a duration before another event occurred. (का उपयोग होता है कि बताने के लिए कि कोई कार्य अतीत में निरंतर जारी था और फिर दूसरा कार्य घटित हुआ)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In the sentence, &amp;quot;when the rain started&amp;quot; is the event that occurred after the ongoing action of playing for two hours.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The other options do not fit as appropriately: &lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Were playing&lt;/strong&gt; indicates a past continuous action, but does not emphasize the duration of two hours before the event. (पिछले निरंतर क्रिया को दर्शाता है लेकिन दो घंटे की अवधि पर बल नहीं देता)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Play&lt;/strong&gt; is simple present tense and does not fit the past context of the sentence. (सरल वर्तमान काल है और वाक्य के अतीत संदर्भ में फिट नहीं बैठता)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Played&lt;/strong&gt; is simple past tense and does not emphasize the ongoing action for two hours before the rain started. (सरल भूतकाल है और बारिश शुरू होने से पहले दो घंटे के लिए जारी कार्रवाई पर जोर नहीं देता)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the more appropriate tense is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;have&amp;nbsp;been playing&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complete Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;They &lt;u&gt;&lt;span font-weight:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;have&amp;nbsp;been playing&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; for two hours when the rain started.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 1&lt;/b&gt; i.e. to restore the relationship after a long quarrel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;bury the hatchet&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means to end a conflict or quarrel and become friendly again. (झगड़ा समाप्त करना और फिर से दोस्त बनना)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;After years of rivalry, the two companies decided to bury the hatchet and work together.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;to restore the relationship after a long quarrel&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;refers to the act of reconciling after a dispute or conflict. (लंबे झगड़े के बाद संबंध बहाल करना)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;Peter and Ravi agreed to bury the hatchet after a gap of ten years, deciding it was time to restore their friendship.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt; i.e. to restore the relationship after a long quarrel.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;to live happily ever after &lt;/strong&gt;(सुखपूर्वक जीवन बिताना): Refers to a situation where people live happily for the rest of their lives.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The prince and the princess lived happily ever after.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;to become enemies &lt;/strong&gt;(दुश्मन बनना): Refers to turning into adversaries.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;They were once friends, but a dispute over money caused them to become enemies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;open for a discussion&lt;/strong&gt; (चर्चा के लिए खुला): Refers to being willing to discuss or debate something.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The manager is always open for a discussion about improving team performance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 4&lt;/b&gt; i.e. Uninterested.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Inquisitive&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means having or showing an interest in learning things; curious. (जिज्ञासु)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The inquisitive child asked many questions about the world around her.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Uninterested&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to having or showing no feeling of interest; indifferent. (उदासीन)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; She was uninterested in the conversation and kept looking at her phone.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, we can infer that the opposite of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Inquisitive&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Uninterested&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 4 i.e. Uninterested&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dull&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;नीरस&lt;/span&gt;): Lacking interest or excitement.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The lecture was so dull that many students fell asleep.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Indolent&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;आलसी&lt;/span&gt;): Wanting to avoid activity or exertion; lazy.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; His indolent attitude towards work made him very unproductive.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Curious&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;जिज्ञासु&lt;/span&gt;): Eager to know or learn something.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; She was curious about the new technology and wanted to learn more about it.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note:&amp;nbsp;This is a PYP question, and the official answer key has marked (correct option) as the correct answer, hence we cannot make any changes to it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 3&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;sanguine&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means optimistic or positive, especially in an apparently bad or difficult situation. (आशावादी)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Despite the challenges, she remained sanguine about the future.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Pessimistic&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to tending to see the worst aspect of things or believe that the worst will happen. (निराशावादी)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; His pessimistic attitude made it hard for him to enjoy the trip.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, we can infer that the opposite of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;sanguine&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;pessimistic&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Confident&lt;/strong&gt; (आश्वस्त): Feeling or showing certainty about something.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; She was confident that she would win the competition.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hopeful&lt;/strong&gt; (आशावान): Feeling or inspiring optimism about a future event.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The team is hopeful about their chances in the upcoming match.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Upbeat&lt;/strong&gt; (प्रसन्नचित): Cheerful and optimistic.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; He was in an upbeat mood after receiving good news.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Argumentative&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Dialectic&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the art of investigating or discussing the truth of opinions through logical arguments. (तर्कशास्त्र)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The philosopher engaged in a dialectic to explore the nature of reality.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Argumentative&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;means given to expressing divergent or opposite views, often in a combative or contentious manner. (वितर्कशील)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;She became argumentative when her opinions were challenged.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Argumentative&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Instructive&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;शिक्षाप्रद&lt;/span&gt;): Providing useful information or knowledge.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The seminar was highly instructive and broadened our understanding of the subject.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Constructive&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;रचनात्मक&lt;/span&gt;): Serving a useful purpose; tending to build up.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;He offered constructive criticism that helped improve the project.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Destructive&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;विनाशकारी&lt;/span&gt;): Causing great and irreparable harm or damage.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The hurricane was highly destructive, leaving many homes in ruins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;b&gt;Option 3) Dendrophile&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Dendrophile&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; means a person who loves trees and forests. (वृक्ष प्रेमी)

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;As a dendrophile, John spends most weekends hiking in the forest and observing different tree species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Dendrophile&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;refers to a person who has a special affinity for trees. (वृक्ष प्रेमी)
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;Mary is such a dendrophile that she can identify nearly every tree in her neighborhood by its leaves and bark.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, we can infer that a lover of nature, particularly trees, is called a &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Dendrophile&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;Option 3) Dendrophile&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here are the other options explained along with their Hindi meanings and example sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Autophile&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;स्वयं प्रेमी&lt;/span&gt;): A person who loves solitude or being alone.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; As an autophile, she enjoys spending her evenings reading books in her cozy room.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Green panther&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;हरा तेंदुआ&lt;/span&gt;): This term is not commonly used to describe a lover of nature and might be more of a creative or fictional term.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;The term &amp;#39;Green panther&amp;#39; was used in the novel to describe a nature warrior.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Petrichor&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;पेट्रिचोर&lt;/span&gt;): The pleasant, earthy smell after rain.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; After the long summer drought, the petrichor was a welcome scent in the air.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The sentence states that IMF restructuring programmes ________ winners and losers. This implies that the programmes bring about or cause the existence of winners and losers.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Let&amp;#39;s examine the options:&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1) Create:&lt;/strong&gt; This means to bring (something) into existence. This fits the context perfectly, as the programmes cause the emergence of winners and losers.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2) Celibate:&lt;/strong&gt; This is an adjective meaning abstaining from marriage and sexual relations. It is grammatically and contextually incorrect here.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3) Calibrate:&lt;/strong&gt; This means to adjust (something) precisely for a particular purpose. While programmes are designed, they don&amp;#39;t &amp;quot;calibrate&amp;quot; winners and losers in this sense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4) Calculate:&lt;/strong&gt; This means to determine (the amount or number of something) mathematically. Programmes don&amp;#39;t &amp;quot;calculate&amp;quot; winners and losers; they produce them.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, &amp;quot;create&amp;quot; is the most appropriate word to describe the outcome of the IMF programmes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Complete Passage: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Scholars have long noted that International Monetary Fund (IMF) restructuring programmes (1) &lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;create&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt; winners and losers, but always in (2) &lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;____&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;to different sectors of the economy. For example, the fact that programmes (3) &lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;____&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;to strengthen exports has been shown to favour farmers and business owners over urban middle class state employees like civil servants. The problem with purely (4) &lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;____&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;analyses is highlighted when you look at citizens&amp;rsquo; experiences. One (5) &lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;____&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;of the survey data, covering nine countries in Africa, showed that three out of ten civil servants actually thought IMF reforms made their lives better.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

